{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_27","type":"command_execution","command":"/usr/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' /home/vjovanov/c/forge3/metadata-forge/local_repositories/forge_run_metrics/1841-25660d7e/README.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Metadata Forge Metrics\n\nThis repository stores metrics and run outputs produced by the scripts and AI workflows in the `metadata-forge` project.\n\nAll scripts, `JSON` schemas, and benchmark configurations live in the `metadata-forge` directory. This repo only keeps the resulting data so it can be tracked, versioned, and analyzed over time.\n\nProject link : https://ol-bitbucket.us.oracle.com/projects/G/repos/graal-enterprise/browse/metadata-forge\n\n## Repository goals\n\n- Persist metrics from `metadata-forge` script runs.\n- Track performance and behavior of predefined benchmark suites.\n- Keep metrics data separate from the main codebase for easier analysis and history tracking.\n\n## Layout\n\n```console\nmetadata-forge-metrics/\n├─ script_run_metrics/\n└─ benchmark_run_metrics/\n```\n\n### `script_run_metrics/`\n\nStores metrics from regular script runs in `metadata-forge`.\n\n- Each AI script has a `JSON` file named after the script.\n- Each object in the `JSON` will represent metrics of one run for a single library version.\n- Example:\n  - `script_run_metrics/new_library_support.json` – metrics for a script that manages or tests adding new library support.\n\n### `benchmark_run_metrics/`\n\nStores metrics from predefined benchmark configurations.\n\n- Each benchmark has a JSON file named after it.\n- Example:\n  - `benchmark_run_metrics/metadata_entries_hunter.json` – metrics for a benchmark suite that tracks performance or behavior when adding new library support, using a strategy that favors generating tests which tend to cover as many metadata entries as possible.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
